{"parentUuid":"b5055e45-dd67-4d91-89f4-e54c54007b35","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"acecf48983d445221","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcqpMxpym88FR4Uw41yFF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0174cBfHUetDuN1ibXGdFHXq","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd \"c:/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test\" && git diff HEAD -- scripts/ci/guard-source-markers.sh scripts/ci/dast-review.sh src/api/errors.py","description":"Diffs of CI scripts and errors.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5215,"cache_read_input_tokens":76309,"output_tokens":2340,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5215},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2340,"cache_read_input_tokens":76309,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5215,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5215,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcqpMwMS1JAN53dGUeVwS","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"163e0b03-b058-4d6f-88ba-79649dd18922","timestamp":"2026-07-09T04:02:16.883Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"163e0b03-b058-4d6f-88ba-79649dd18922","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"8a0970a7-992a-482d-b1fb-9fa84d4f1b3d","agentId":"acecf48983d445221","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0174cBfHUetDuN1ibXGdFHXq","type":"tool_result","content":"diff --git a/scripts/ci/dast-review.sh b/scripts/ci/dast-review.sh\nindex a1153ad..39b3ddd 100644\n--- a/scripts/ci/dast-review.sh\n+++ b/scripts/ci/dast-review.sh\n@@ -32,7 +32,15 @@ budget_json='{\"high\":0,\"medium\":5,\"low\":20,\"informational\":100}'\n # ZAP baseline JSON shape: {\"site\":[{\"@name\":URL,\"alerts\":[{\"name\",\"riskcode\":\"0|1|2|3\",\"count\":\"N\"}]}]}\n # riskcode + count are STRINGS in ZAP's report — coerce with tonumber. Sum count per severity across\n # every site; list the distinct alert names that pushed a severity over its cap.\n-jq -n --slurpfile cap \"$CAP\" --argjson b \"$budget_json\" --arg t \"$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\" '\n+# U-14: fold in the target-reachability probe dast-capture writes. A false there means the\n+# spider seeded on a non-page (bare root when the UI is at /dashboard), so a within-budget\n+# verdict scanned nothing real — surfaced as a WARN below, still advisory (never a gate).\n+# Read the sidecar into a variable (default {} when absent — backward compatible).\n+probe_json='{}'\n+if [ -f .pipeline/dast-target-probe.json ] && jq -e . .pipeline/dast-target-probe.json >/dev/null 2>&1; then\n+  probe_json=\"$(jq -c '.' .pipeline/dast-target-probe.json)\"\n+fi\n+jq -n --slurpfile cap \"$CAP\" --argjson b \"$budget_json\" --argjson probe \"$probe_json\" --arg t \"$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)\" '\n   ({\"3\":\"high\",\"2\":\"medium\",\"1\":\"low\",\"0\":\"informational\"}) as $sevmap\n   | [ $cap[0].site // [] | .[] | .alerts // [] | .[]\n       | {sev: ($sevmap[(.riskcode|tostring)] // \"informational\"),\n@@ -46,19 +54,26 @@ jq -n --slurpfile cap \"$CAP\" --argjson b \"$budget_json\" --arg t \"$(date -u +%Y-%\n       | select($n > $capn)\n       | {severity: $s, count: $n, budget: $capn,\n          alerts: ($alerts | map(select(.sev == $s) | .name) | unique)} ] as $over\n+  | ({\"target_reached\": true} + ($probe // {})) as $p\n   | {status: \"advisory\",\n      ran_at: $t,\n      target: $target,\n+     target_reached: ($p.target_reached),\n+     target_status: ($p.status // null),\n      alerts_by_severity: $by_sev,\n      over_budget: $over,\n      within_budget: (($over | length) == 0)}\n ' > \"$OUT\"\n \n OVER=$(jq '.over_budget | length' \"$OUT\" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)\n+REACHED=$(jq -r '.target_reached' \"$OUT\" 2>/dev/null || echo true)\n+if [ \"$REACHED\" = \"false\" ]; then\n+  echo \"[dast-review] ADVISORY: DAST target was NOT reached (HTTP $(jq -r '.target_status // \"?\"' \"$OUT\")) — the passive scan did not traverse the real page; treat 'within budget' as uninformative. Set DAST_TARGET_URL to the served route. Surface in the PR (advisory). See $OUT.\" >&2\n+fi\n if [ \"${OVER:-0}\" -gt 0 ]; then\n   HI=$(jq -r '[.over_budget[] | select(.severity==\"high\")] | length' \"$OUT\" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)\n   echo \"[dast-review] ADVISORY: $OVER severity band(s) over budget (${HI} at HIGH) — surface in the PR (advisory, non-blocking). See $OUT.\" >&2\n-else\n+elif [ \"$REACHED\" != \"false\" ]; then\n   echo \"[dast-review] within budget (target: $(jq -r '.target // \"n/a\"' \"$OUT\")).\"\n fi\n exit 0\ndiff --git a/scripts/ci/guard-source-markers.sh b/scripts/ci/guard-source-markers.sh\nindex ec6b942..cfc09f0 100644\n--- a/scripts/ci/guard-source-markers.sh\n+++ b/scripts/ci/guard-source-markers.sh\n@@ -5,10 +5,10 @@\n # The M5 hazard: a debugging agent replaced a money-path fix with the original buggy\n # code tagged with an experimental scratch-revert marker (a TEMP-style prefix combined\n # with a REVERT suffix — see the pattern list below) to demonstrate a repro, then capped\n-# before restoring it — leaving the money path broken while the build stayed green (no signal).\n-# It was caught only because a human re-grepped for SAVEPOINT. This hook makes that\n-# signal deterministic: it greps the change set (tracked diff + untracked files vs HEAD,\n-# the same set the rest of the pipeline scopes to) for danger markers and blocks.\n+# before restoring it — leaving the money path broken while the build stayed green (no\n+# signal). It was caught only because a human re-grepped for SAVEPOINT. This hook makes\n+# that signal deterministic: it greps the change set (tracked diff + untracked files vs\n+# HEAD, the same set the rest of the pipeline scopes to) for danger markers and blocks.\n #\n # Two roles (same logic):\n #   1. deployment-gate.sh sources/invokes it → a HARD deploy block (the money guarantee).\n@@ -16,13 +16,14 @@\n #      can stop, that it left a marker in the tree (exit 2 feeds stderr back to the model).\n #\n # Markers matched (word-boundary, case-insensitive; see the MARKERS regex below for the\n-# exact patterns — described here rather than spelled out literally, so this comment\n-# doesn't trip the very check it documents): a TEMP-style scratch tag combined with a\n-# REVERT suffix (optionally via an extra prefix word); a REVERT tag combined with an ME\n-# suffix; an XXX tag combined with a REVERT suffix; a phrase meaning the change must not\n-# be committed; and HACK/FIXME tags meaning remove-or-fix-before-shipping.\n-# Plain TODO/FIXME/XXX are NOT matched — those are normal and blocking on them would just\n-# train people to bypass the gate. Only experimental-revert or must-not-ship-class markers block.\n+# exact shapes — U-05: this prose deliberately DESCRIBES them instead of spelling them,\n+# so the scaffold copy of this file never trips the guard itself): a TEMP tag combined\n+# with a REVERT suffix (optionally via an extra prefix word); a REVERT tag combined with\n+# an ME suffix; an XXX tag combined with a REVERT suffix; a phrase meaning the change\n+# must not be committed; a HACK tag with a REMOVE suffix; a FIXME tag scoped to\n+# before-commit. Plain TODO/FIXME/XXX are NOT matched — those are normal and blocking on\n+# them would just train people to bypass the gate. Only experimental-revert or\n+# must-not-ship-class markers block.\n #\n # Exit: 0 = clean (or no change set / not a pipeline project) · 2 = marker found (BLOCK).\n set -uo pipefail\n@@ -45,14 +46,19 @@ else\n   [ -f .pipeline/state.json ] || exit 0\n fi\n \n-# Danger-marker pattern. Anchored to experimental-revert or must-not-ship intent, not ordinary TODOs.\n+# Danger-marker pattern. Anchored to experimental-revert or must-not-ship intent, not\n+# ordinary TODOs. (The regex itself does not self-match — verified in marker-guard.sh.)\n MARKERS='TEMP[-_ ]?(PREFIX[-_ ]?)?REVERT|REVERT[-_ ]?ME|XXX[-_ ]?REVERT|DO[-_ ]?NOT[-_ ]?COMMIT|HACK[-_ ]?REMOVE|FIXME[-_ ]?BEFORE[-_ ]?COMMIT'\n \n # Change set = tracked diff (added lines only) + untracked files vs HEAD. We scan ADDED\n # diff lines (leading '+') so a marker being REMOVED in the diff doesn't false-positive,\n-# and untracked files in full. Exclude this hook itself and test fixtures/suites, which\n-# legitimately contain marker strings as test data.\n-EXCLUDE='(^|/)(tests/|.*\\.pipeline/|global-hooks/guard-source-markers\\.sh)'\n+# and untracked files in full. Exclude this hook's own definition files by path — the\n+# repo-of-record copy AND the per-project scaffold copy bootstrap writes to scripts/ci/\n+# (U-05: the M3 run false-blocked on its own fresh scaffold because only the\n+# global-hooks path was excluded) — plus test fixtures/suites, which legitimately\n+# contain marker strings as test data. The exclusion is pinned to this one filename: a\n+# real marker planted anywhere else in scripts/ci/ still blocks.\n+EXCLUDE='(^|/)(tests/|.*\\.pipeline/|(global-hooks|scripts/ci)/guard-source-markers\\.sh)'\n \n hits=\"\"\n \n@@ -82,7 +88,7 @@ done < <(git ls-files -z --others --exclude-standard 2>/dev/null || true)\n \n if [ -n \"$hits\" ]; then\n   echo \"Blocked: the change set contains an experimental / revert marker (audit E3) — a\" >&2\n-  echo \"reverted or must-not-ship fix must never ship. Restore the real fix (prove repros in\" >&2\n+  echo \"reverted or do-not-commit fix must never ship. Restore the real fix (prove repros in\" >&2\n   echo \"a scratch copy, never in the tree), then re-run. Offending lines:\" >&2\n   printf '%s\\n' \"$hits\" >&2\n   exit 2\ndiff --git a/src/api/errors.py b/src/api/errors.py\nindex d1c0f75..675838c 100644\n--- a/src/api/errors.py\n+++ b/src/api/errors.py\n@@ -39,6 +39,21 @@ def _envelope(code: str, message: str, request_id: str) -> dict:\n     return {\"error\": {\"code\": code, \"message\": message, \"requestId\": request_id}}\n \n \n+class AppError(HTTPException):\n+    \"\"\"An `HTTPException` carrying an explicit `app_code`, for the cases where\n+    `_STATUS_TO_CODE`'s status->code map can't express the distinction —\n+    `429` already maps to `rate_limited` (the Tier-2 throttle), but a quota\n+    rejection needs its own, distinct `quota_exceeded` code on the same\n+    status. `handle_http_exception` prefers `app_code` over the status map\n+    when present, so this is the minimal single-boundary extension rather\n+    than reshaping the map itself.\n+    \"\"\"\n+\n+    def __init__(self, status_code: int, *, app_code: str, detail: str, headers: dict | None = None) -> None:\n+        super().__init__(status_code=status_code, detail=detail, headers=headers)\n+        self.app_code = app_code\n+\n+\n def register_error_handlers(app: FastAPI) -> None:\n     \"\"\"Register the centralized exception handlers on `app`.\n \n@@ -63,9 +78,14 @@ def register_error_handlers(app: FastAPI) -> None:\n \n     @app.exception_handler(StarletteHTTPException)\n     async def handle_http_exception(request: Request, exc: StarletteHTTPException) -> JSONResponse:\n-        \"\"\"Map a raised `HTTPException` (auth, rate-limit, not-found, ...) to the envelope.\"\"\"\n+        \"\"\"Map a raised `HTTPException` (auth, rate-limit, not-found, ...) to the envelope.\n+\n+        Prefers an explicit `app_code` (set by `AppError`) over the status->code\n+        map — this is what lets two different exceptions share one HTTP status\n+        (`429 rate_limited` vs. `429 quota_exceeded`) with distinct client-facing codes.\n+        \"\"\"\n         request_id = _request_id(request)\n-        code = _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(exc.status_code, \"error\")\n+        code = getattr(exc, \"app_code\", None) or _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(exc.status_code, \"error\")\n         message = exc.detail if isinstance(exc.detail, str) else \"request failed\"\n         return JSONResponse(\n             status_code=exc.status_code,\n@@ -97,4 +117,4 @@ def register_error_handlers(app: FastAPI) -> None:\n         )\n \n \n-__all__ = [\"register_error_handlers\", \"HTTPException\"]\n+__all__ = [\"register_error_handlers\", \"HTTPException\", \"AppError\"]","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"f695be6d-fb5c-429b-abec-ad8a8f2955e7","timestamp":"2026-07-09T04:02:17.109Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"163e0b03-b058-4d6f-88ba-79649dd18922","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"f695be6d-fb5c-429b-abec-ad8a8f2955e7","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"acecf48983d445221","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcqpQoawQah77y7AuXmeX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6928,"cache_read_input_tokens":81524,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6928,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcqpQn4R5cPREPJSN8i2t","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"df92efe8-bec6-4701-9158-5e476ac93783","timestamp":"2026-07-09T04:02:48.382Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/metric-quotas"}
{"parentUuid":"df92efe8-bec6-4701-9158-5e476ac93783","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"acecf48983d445221","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcqpQoawQah77y7AuXmeX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I traced every changed contract across its call sites. Here's what I found.\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. CI coverage floor is never enforced — `<COVERAGE_FLOOR>` placeholder is unfilled and no `--cov-fail-under` flag exists\n**File:** `.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml:66` (and its comment at :68)\n**Summary:** The `build-and-test` job runs `poetry run pytest --cov=src --cov-branch` with no `--cov-fail-under` argument; the `<COVERAGE_FLOOR>` token survives only inside the comment on line 68. `pyproject.toml`'s `[tool.coverage.run]` has no `fail_under`, and there is no `addopts`. So coverage is *measured* but never *gated*.\n**Failure scenario:** A PR that drops combined line coverage to, say, 40% still turns the `build-and-test` job green, because pytest exits 0 regardless of coverage. Meanwhile `CLAUDE.md:30` explicitly claims the deploy/merge bar is \"tests pass at >= 85% coverage.\" CI and the documented gate disagree; the 85% floor the comment says CI \"rides\" is not actually ridden anywhere (CI, pyproject, or a local addopts). Note: this line is unchanged vs HEAD (this diff only added the `mutation` job), so it is a pre-existing gap the change-set inherits, not one it introduces.\n\n### 2. RLS backstop on `events` / `usage_rollup` is inert for the app role, while `quotas` (0003) correctly forces it — inconsistent convention\n**File:** `alembic/versions/0003_create_quotas_and_api_key_scope.py:65` vs `0001_...py` and `0002_...py`\n**Summary:** Migration 0003 adds `ALTER TABLE quotas FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` and its docstring spells out *why*: `meterly_app` is the table owner, and a table owner bypasses **non-FORCE** RLS regardless of `NOBYPASSRLS`, leaving the policy inert for the app role. By that exact reasoning, `events_tenant_isolation` (0001) and `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation` (0002) — which are `ENABLE`d but never `FORCE`d — are inert for the owning app role in production.\n**Failure scenario:** If any `events_repo`/rollup query ever loses its explicit `api_key_id = :api_key_id` filter (the exact \"primary control missing\" case the RLS layer is claimed to backstop, and which `test_quotas_rls_backstop.py` proves *for quotas*), events/usage_rollup would leak cross-tenant rows in prod, because the owner bypasses their non-FORCE policy. The tests can't catch it: they connect as the testcontainers superuser (bypasses RLS entirely) except the one quotas backstop test that spins up a dedicated `NOBYPASSRLS` role — and there is no equivalent NOBYPASSRLS test for events/usage_rollup. Pre-existing (0001/0002 unchanged), but 0003 makes the inconsistency concrete and now the naming/convention is split across the three migrations.\n\n## Everything else in the traced set checked out\n- **AppError / 429 header consistency:** Both 429 raisers set `Retry-After` (`QuotaExceededError` in `events_service.py:63`, tier-2 throttle in `rate_limit.py:174`), and `handle_http_exception` (`errors.py:88,93`) now prefers `app_code` and passes `exc.headers` through. `quota_exceeded` vs `rate_limited` correctly share status 429. No raiser passes a non-string `detail` that would bypass the envelope.\n- **`AuthenticatedPrincipal.scope`:** New field has a default (`\"ingest\"`); the only real constructor (`api_key.py:82`) passes `scope=record.scope`, and the three direct test constructions (`tests/test_auth_api_key.py`, `tests/test_rate_limit_fail_open.py`) use kwargs without `scope`, so they keep compiling on the default. `conftest.py`'s `make_api_key` and the k6 quota fixture both thread `scope` correctly.\n- **Quotas dependency ordering:** `routes/quotas.py:26` `_require_admin_and_throttled` composes `require_api_key` → `enforce_tier2_rate_limit` → scope check, matching `events.py:19`'s pattern; router is registered in `main.py:88`; CORS now allows `PUT` (`middleware.py`).\n- **`seed_api_key.py --admin`:** `create_api_key` signature (`api_keys_repo.py:60`) has `scope=\"ingest\"` default; the script passes `scope=scope`. Consistent.\n- **Alembic chain:** 0003 `down_revision=\"0002\"`, policy name `quotas_tenant_isolation` mirrors siblings. Chain is correct.\n- **k6 env-var / bucket contract:** `_run_k6` (`test_perf_k6_load.py:197`) exports `BASE_URL/API_KEY/TARGET_RPS/DURATION/WARMUP_DURATION` — all read by `load_events_quota.js:12-16` (extra JS vars have defaults). The fixture seeds `cust_0..cust_49` / metric `api_calls` (lines 291-302); the JS drives `cust_${__VU % 50}` / `api_calls` (lines 55-58). Buckets and metric match. The direct quota seed skips `scoped_transaction` but works because the testcontainers connection is superuser (bypasses the FORCE RLS), matching the documented setup in `test_quotas_rls_backstop.py`."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6928,"cache_read_input_tokens":81524,"output_tokens":3984,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6928},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3984,"cache_read_input_tokens":81524,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6928,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6928,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcqpQn4R5cPREPJSN8i2t","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"0f6fb90e-6330-49f4-b669-4639d2705174","timestamp":"2026-07-09T04:03:13.498Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch